what @Nora said.
I *think* Shakespeare and his peers (did he have many peers? perhaps better to say contemporaries) wrote in verse (sometimes blank verse) because many of the actors couldn't read, and memorizing verse was easier than prose. So two syllable words were often reduced to one (oft, e'er, e'en) and vice versa. I assume OPE almost always occurs in verse, but it does seem to have occurred often.

